<module>
    <h>dé</h>
    <p><g>dé</g>
        <en>what</en> is a question word.</p>
    <section id="forms">
        <h>forms</h>
        <p>In post-1970s Neo-Gaelic orthography, the spelling has been standardised to <g>dè</g>,
            with a grave accent.</p>
        <p>In Lewis Gaelic, <g>dé</g> is pronounced like English ‘day’, rather than English
            ‘jay’.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section>
            <h>complement</h>
            <p>The complement of <g>dé</g> is introduced by the relative particle <a
                    href="?gd=a^relative"><g>a</g></a>.</p>
            <module id="dee_a_tha">
                <h>dé a tha ... ?</h>
                <p><g>dé [a] <a href="?gd=bi">tha</a> ... ?</g>
                    <en>what is ... ?</en></p>
                <p>Examples where <g>dé</g> stands for the subject, cf. <en> what is there ...
                    ?</en> – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Dé tha air an teine? Tha gual air an teine.</gd>
                            <tr>What is (there) on the fire? There is coal on the fire.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Dé tha ceàrr air a’ ghille seo? Tha a cheann goirt.</gd>
                            <tr>What is (there) wrong with this boy? His head is sore.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Dé tha anns a’ bhocsa sin? Tha uighean anns a’ bhocsa.</gd>
                            <tr>What is (there) in that box? There are eggs in the box.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
                <p>Examples where <g>dé</g> stands for something else – <xl>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Dé tha Seònaid a’ dèanamh anns an taigh? Tha i a’ cluich air an
                                làr.</gd>
                            <tr>What is Janet doing in the house? She is playing on the floor.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <gd>Dé tha seo? Tha botul.</gd>
                            <tr>What is this? It’s a bottle.</tr>
                            <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                        </li>
                    </xl>
                </p>
                <module id="dee_a_bha">
                    <h>dé a bha ... ?</h>
                    <p>The past tense variant of <g>dé a tha ... ?</g> is <g>dé a bha ... ?</g>
                        <en>what was ... ?</en>.</p>
                    <p>Examples where <g>dé</g> stands for the subject, cf. <en> what was there ...
                            ?</en> – <xl>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Dé bha anns a’ bhocsa? Bha uighean anns a’ bhocsa.</gd>
                                <tr>What was (there) in the box? There were eggs in the box.</tr>
                                <ref text="617">td. 21 [229]</ref>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Dé bha air a’ chnoc? Bha taigh mór air a’ chnoc.</gd>
                                <tr>What was (there) on the hill? There was a big house on the
                                    hill.</tr>
                                <ref text="617">td. 20 [adapted]</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl></p>
                    <p>Examples where <g>dé</g> stands for something else – <xl>
                            <li>
                                <gd>Dé bha Seumas a’ dèanamh an dé. Bha e ag obair gu trang anns an
                                    achadh.</gd>
                                <tr>What was James doing yesterday? He was working busily in the
                                    field.</tr>
                                <ref text="617">td. 14 [adapted]</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </p>
                </module>
            </module>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="uses-root">
            <h>root</h>
            <p><g>dé</g> can be used as the root of a direct question.</p>
            <p>Some examples where <g>dé</g> stands for the subject – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Dé bha anns a’ bhocsa? Bha uighean anns a’ bhocsa.</gd>
                        <tr>What was in the box? There were eggs in the box.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 21 [229]</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
            <p>Some examples where <g>dé</g> stands for something else – <xl>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Dé tha Seumas a’ dèanamh an diugh. Tha e ag obair gu trang anns an
                            achadh.</gd>
                        <tr>What is James doing today? He is working busily in the field.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 14</ref>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <gd>Dé tha seo? Tha botul.</gd>
                        <tr>What is this? It’s a bottle.</tr>
                        <ref text="617">td. 20</ref>
                    </li>
                </xl>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>


